Use **`dotnet-trace`** to collect `HttpClient` event source diagnostics:

```bash
# Install the tool (if not already)
dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace

# Collect HttpClient + networking events
dotnet-trace collect \
  -p <PID> \
  --providers "System.Net.Http,Microsoft-Extensions-Logging"
```

This captures per-request events including URL, status code, and duration.

**For richer detail**, add `HttpHandlerDiagnosticListener` in your code:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("downstream")
    .AddHttpMessageHandler(() => new LoggingDelegatingHandler());
```

Or more simply, enable **HTTP logging middleware**:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpLogging(o =>
{
    o.LoggingFields = HttpLoggingFields.All;
});
```

And set logging levels in `appsettings.json`:

```json
{
  "Logging": {
    "LogLevel": {
      "System.Net.Http.HttpClient": "Information"
    }
  }
}
```

At `Information` level, `IHttpClientFactory` logs request method, URI, status code, and elapsed time for every call — exactly what you need to correlate the 500s.
